article.headline: New Mexico 49, Utah 46
article.story:
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Abbie Letz's shot and New Mexico's
season are both headed in the right direction.

Letz, unable to hit shots near or far most of this season, hit a
3-pointer with 2:25 left Thursday night that helped the Lobos beat
No. 25 Utah 49-46.

Letz had three 3-pointers in the game and finished with 11
points. She and Lindsey Arndt, who posted a double-double with 12
points and 12 rebounds, led New Mexico to a win it needed to stay
in the Mountain West Conference title chase and in the running for
a postseason bid.

"Nationally it gives you recognition. It's big in the
conference, big in the (conference tournament) seeding," New
Mexico coach Don Flanagan said.

For Letz, who came into the game hitting a meager 25 percent of
her shots, it was a game where almost everything went right.

"My shot feels a lot better the last couple of weeks," she
said. "It felt normal, whereas early in the season there was no
telling where it was going to go."

New Mexico (15-7, 7-2 MWC) held the Utes (19-5, 9-1) without a
field goal for the final 11 minutes of the first half to take a
25-14 lead. The only points the Utes got in that stretch were a
pair of free throws by Kim Smith with 6:10 left in the half.

"They beat us to the rebounds and they beat us to the ball,"
said Utah coach Elaine Elliott. "If you're not hitting shots,
other battles have to be won and we didn't win enough of them."

Smith finished with 13 points and 11 rebounds and Shona Thorburn
added 11 points for the Utes. It wasn't enough for a Utah team that
set a pair of first half season lows for scoring and shooting
percentage (21.7)

Utah's scoring drought continued through the first three minutes
of the second half, but back-to-back 3-pointers by Lana Sitterud
got the offense rolling.

The Utes went on a 13-3 run to cut the New Mexico lead to 33-29
but New Mexico countered with seven straight points. A 3-pointer by
Mandi Moore made 40-29 with 9:25 left.

Utah, which had won nine straight and 13 of its last 14 games,
wasn't done. A 15-4 run, the final two points a pair of free throws
by Carley Marshall tied it at 44 with 2:52 remaining.

Letz then hit her third 3-pointer of the game with and teammate
Melissa Forest scored on a baseline jumper with 1:47 left.

Smith hit two free throws and after a miss by Forest, the Utes
had a final shot at a tie. The ball ended up in Kelsy Stireman's
hands and she missed a 3 with a second left.

Elliott said Smith was supposed to take the last shot.

"We wanted to flare out Kim but (Stireman) got a nice shot off.
I thought it was going in," Elliott said.

Arndt, who was scoreless in Utah's 52-43 win in Salt Lake City
last month, scored all of her points and had nine rebounds in the
first half. She also did a solid defensive job on Smith in the
first half, holding her to the two free throws.

"She was the most energized player on the floor," Elliott
said.
